[3]
Date: Tue, 8 Nov 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Xinhua via People's Daily on line, 8 Nov 2005 [edited]
<http://english.people.com.cn/200511/08/eng20051108_219696.html>

China's Health Minister Gao Qiang on Monday [7 Nov 2005] ordered
health departments across the country to act quickly in the
prevention and control of human infection with bird flu.
Addressing a nationally televised conference, Gao ordered them to
strengthen work [in 3 key areas], namely monitoring, control, and
treatment, stressing that early action is crucial in all of them.
"The health departments should work synchronously with the
agricultural departments once they learn about the outbreak of an
epidemic among animals," said Gao. He said health personnel should
arrive at the spot, conduct an investigation, and proceed to handle
the epidemic at the same time, together with personnel from the
agricultural departments.
He ordered the health departments to maintain an efficient
information-sharing mechanism with relevant departments, including
civil aviation and transportation departments, to ensure quick action.
Gao said in case any humans are infected with bird flu, the health
personnel should [use] traditional Chinese medicines [in] treating
them. "There should also be an expert panel to provide technical
support," he said.
Gao also stressed the importance of promoting publicity of epidemic
prevention knowledge and actively strengthening international and
regional cooperation.
The ministry has invited the World Health Organization to support the
ongoing investigation of 3 cases in Hunan Province currently
diagnosed as "pneumonia of unknown causes."
"After conducting comprehensive analysis, experts said although the 3
cases are diagnosed as pneumonia of unknown causes at present, the
possibility of human infection by the highly pathogenic H5N1 strain
of bird flu cannot be ruled out," a spokesman for the ministry said
on Sunday.
A dialogue is underway between China and the WHO to determine what
this assistance should be, according to WHO's Beijing Office on
Monday.
